‚ÄúI‚Äôm in a unique position. It‚Äôs important for me to reflect the public health needs of our state, but I also intimately understand the toll this is taking on small businesses and the economy.‚Äù Dr. David Wheeler, President, Wyoming Medical Society For today's installment of WyoLight, I had the opportunity to speak with Dr. David Wheeler, President of the Wyoming Medical Society.  Healthcare Providers have the deepest understanding of the crisis we face, and also understand firsthand the impact it has had on small businesses across Wyoming.  While much of our discussion centered around the harsh reality of this virus, we got to reflect on how well our doctors and health care providers work together across the state to provide the highest quality service to the people of Wyoming. We have unique challenges here in Wyoming, but we work together and come up with solutions that are best for Wyoming and its people.

‚ÄúTo work in the hospitality industry, you‚Äôve got to be a warrior.‚Äù ‚Äì Chris Brown, Executive Director of the Wyoming Lodging & Restaurant Association This week we are launching a new series called ‚ÄòWyoLight‚Äô to highlight Wyoming industries and hear how they are being impacted by COVID-19. As Wyoming Lodging and Restaurant Association's Chris Brown said during our inaugural WyoLight conversation, folks who work in hotels, restaurants, recreation, travel and tourism and other hospitality industries are true warriors who have gone through tough times before.  That being said, Chris had an important point that hospitality ‚Äúcan weather a terrible season, but we can‚Äôt weather a season that doesn‚Äôt happen at all.‚Äù There are many ways we can support restaurants and small businesses while they are still shut down including ordering food to-go, purchasing gift certificates and writing positive reviews online.  For a full list of ideas, check out the guide on our website: https://lummisforwyoming.com/covid/

Classy statement by Wyoming 4-H. Proud to have been a 4-Her and a 4-H mom (and very much looking forward to being a 4-H grandma).  Remember, fellow former 4-Hers:  I pledge my head to clearer thinking, My heart to greater loyalty, My hands to larger service, and my health to better living, for my club, my community, my country, and my world.Dear 4-H Family, From now through the end of month (March 31st), all face-to-face 4-H activities are postponed or must use technology methods (Zoom, Google Hangouts, etc.).  This includes all project, club, committee, council, foundation meetings, etc. This short hiatus will allow our local medical professionals to better manage and address the effects of this particular virus.  Our decisions are not motivated by politics, money, the media, fear, or anything else other than being a good citizen and contributing to the greater effort of the health and well-being of our family, friends, loved-ones, neighbors, and communities. Truly we get to apply the 4-H pledge in our daily lives.

Wyoming has lots to brag about on International Women‚Äôs Day. We are the first state to grant women the right to vote, a full 50 years before the 19th Amendment.  And Wyoming women were pioneers in law, business and politics (including): ‚úîÔ∏èFirst woman Governor ‚úîÔ∏èFirst woman Justice of the Peace ‚úîÔ∏èFirst woman Bailiff  I am thinking of one of my mentors today, Ellen Crowley, an undersung hero of the Equality State. Ellen was State Librarian from 1949-1951 and an Assistant Wyoming Attorney General from 1955-1959. She was small in stature but made her presence known with super high heels and an unmistakable wit.  Ellen was the first woman lawyer in the Wyoming AG‚Äôs office and the first female law clerk in the U.S. District Courts in Wyoming. She served in the Wyoming House of Representatives from 1973-1987 and as President of the Laramie County Bar Association from 1974-1975.  Would love to hear about your female Wyoming heroes if you‚Äôd like to share in the comments.

Talk about a #ThrowbackThursday: My first job out of college was working for Cotton Rosser and the Flying U Rodeo Company.  A modern day Buffalo Bill Cody. A true showman of the spirit of the American West.Just got off the phone with my friend Cotton Rosser, Cotton has  inspired so many people including myself, and continues to do so at the young age of 91.   Here is a story that was done on Cotton last year in part by PRSN But what most spectators won‚Äôt know is that one man has produced nearly every other rodeo in the Golden State at one time or another. Since Cotton Rosser bought the Flying U Rodeo Company 60 years ago, he has become a legend in the rodeo world. Everyone knows his name. "The loveliest people are in rodeos," says Rosser. "They do it because they love it, and it‚Äôs a Western way of life. They love the animals and the horses and the outdoors, and the atmosphere of rodeo is just barbecues and fun." At 91 years old, Rosser has been honored by nearly every cowboy, rodeo or rancher hall of fame there is. He has a place in the Hall of Great Westerners, alongside John Wayne, Ronald Reagan and Dwight D. Eisenhower. But he was actually born a city kid in Long Beach in 1928. He grew up reading books about cowboys and watching Gene Autry, Will Rogers and Hopalong Cassidy. ‚ÄúI wanted to be a cowboy my whole life,‚Äù says Rosser. He was barely a teenager when he got a job on Santa Catalina Island, on a ranch owned by William Wrigley of chewing gum fame. At the time there were no cowboys for hire -- they were off fighting in World War II. So they gave young Cotton Rosser a chance, since he only had school half-days. ‚ÄúI used to clean stalls, clean the manure, and they let me ride a donkey named Jack,‚Äù says Rosser. And the donkey was just the beginning. Soon, he graduated to riding bulls and saddle broncs, and by the time he was a student at Cal Poly San Luis Obispo, he turned pro. Rosser competed in rodeos all over the country. ‚Äú[The] Cow Palace, Las Vegas, Reno, Calgary Stampede,‚Äù he says. ‚ÄúAll the rodeos -- Cheyenne, [and] Pendleton.‚Äù In 1951, he even won the Grand National Rodeo‚Äôs all-around cowboy title. Then, in 1955, he broke both his legs in an accident while digging post holes on his Marysville ranch north of Sacramento. That ended his rodeo career. ‚Äú[It was the] best thing that ever happened to me,‚Äù Rosser says. He bought the Flying U Rodeo Company and started his career putting on shows and raising rodeo animals. Today, the Flying U is the oldest continually operating stock contracting company in the United States. Since he joined the rodeo world in the 1940s, Rosser has seen the sport change, and at times it seemed like fans were slipping away. To bring more people to the arena, the Flying U Rodeo Company got creative. It added high production value, loud rock 'n' roll, audience engagement and freestyle motocross -- dirt bike riders performing flips off tall ramps. And in recent years, Cotton says these new attractions have boosted attendance. That includes the Grand National Rodeo at the Cow Palace.  ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs very action-packed,‚Äù he says. ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs always something new ! ProRodeo Hall of Fame stock contractor Cotton Rosser has been named the 2019 Legend of ProRodeo. Rosser was honored at the 12th annual Wrangler Gold Buckle Gala on Dec. 2 at the South Point Grand Ballroom in Las Vegas. ‚ÄúThis is a wonderful, great honor to receive,‚Äù said Rosser, 91. Rosser was inducted into the ProRodeo Hall of Fame in 1995. Rosser and his son, Reno, operate the Flying U Rodeo and Rosser Rodeo stock contracting companies based in Marysville, Calif. They produce about 50 rodeos a year. ‚ÄúI‚Äôm just the PR man now,‚Äù Cotton said with a chuckle. ‚ÄúI never imagined my rodeo career would be like this. I‚Äôm the richest guy in the world with memories and friends. I‚Äôve loved every minute of the rodeo business and I would do it all over again. It has been a great experience.‚Äù Rosser is the 14th man to be honored with the ProRodeo Legend award, following Jake Barnes, Jim Shoulders, Clem McSpadden, Harry Vold, Larry Mahan, Shawn Davis, Dean Oliver, Donnie Gay, Benny Binion, Mel Potter, Neal Gay, Michael Gaughan, and Keith Martin. Rosser is a pioneer in the rodeo industry who was ahead of his time in developing the entertainment side of rodeo. Rosser received the PRCA Donita Barnes Contract Personnel Lifetime Achievement award in 2015. ‚ÄúA lot of rodeos we have, we have had for 60 years, like the Cow Palace, Red Bluff (in California) and Reno (Nev.),‚Äù said Rosser, who served on the PRCA Board of Directors for many years. ‚ÄúThey even put a statue up in Reno of me (in 2014). It just doesn‚Äôt get much better. I have raised a good family and I really tried to help rodeo. Some people say if you‚Äôve seen one rodeo, you have seen them all, and I have always said I don‚Äôt think that‚Äôs quite true. Rodeo is the greatest sport in the world, and I‚Äôm glad to have been a part of it for the last 70 years.‚Äù Rosser still rides a horse into the arena, and he wouldn‚Äôt have it any other way. ‚ÄúRodeo is the only thing I know,‚Äù Rosser said. ‚ÄúIt doesn‚Äôt get better than that when you ride into the arena and they play the national anthem and there is a full house,‚Äù he said. For more than 60 years, Rosser has been known for his spectacular, flamboyant opening ceremonies at rodeos on the West Coast and for many years at the National Finals Rodeo. Rosser is considered the ‚ÄúP.T. Barnum‚Äù of professional rodeo. He has searched out ideas from sources as remote from the sport as ice shows and circuses, looking for that special something he can add to his productions. The other side of Rosser is his history as a top cowboy, who started competing in all of rodeo‚Äôs standard events as a teenager and later as a member of his college rodeo team at Cal Poly University-San Luis Obispo. As a professional, he won buckles, saddles and trophies. Among his many titles, one of Rosser‚Äôs highlights was winning the all-around title at the 1951 Grand National Rodeo in San Francisco. Rosser purchased the Flying U Rodeo Ranch in 1956, which is now the oldest continuing rodeo livestock company in the United States. In 1985, Rosser was named PRCA Stock Contractor of the Year.
